<h2>The Origin: A Tomato-Shaped Timer</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Tell the origin story: Francesco Cirillo, a university student in the late 1980s, struggling to focus. He picked up a tomato-shaped kitchen timer (pomodoro is Italian for tomato), set it for 25 minutes, and committed to working on one task until it rang. The technique grew from that experiment into a widely-used productivity framework.]</p>

<h2>Why It Works</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Explain the psychological mechanisms: attention restoration theory (the mind needs rest cycles to sustain focus), the Zeigarnik effect (unfinished tasks stay mentally active, so the ticking timer keeps the brain engaged), and decision fatigue (committing to one task eliminates the constant micro-decisions about what to do next). Keep this readable — avoid academic jargon.]</p>

<h2>The Exact Steps</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Walk through the method precisely: (1) choose a single task, (2) set a <a href="/timer/25-minutes/">25-minute timer</a>, (3) work on only that task until the timer rings, (4) take a <a href="/timer/5-minutes/">5-minute break</a> — stand up, move, don't look at your phone, (5) after 4 rounds, take a 15–30 minute long break. Use the <a href="/pomodoro/">Pomodoro timer on Timerrapp</a> to track all of this automatically.]</p>

<h2>The Four Most Common Mistakes</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Cover: (1) checking your phone during the break, which defeats the restoration purpose; (2) skipping the break when you're "in flow" — this undermines the structure the technique relies on; (3) cramming multiple tasks into one session instead of committing to one; (4) not writing down the task before starting, which lets your brain drift to other concerns mid-session.]</p>

<h2>Variations Worth Knowing</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Briefly cover: the 52/17 rule (52 minutes focus, 17 minutes break, based on research by the Draugiem Group), 90-minute ultradian blocks (based on the brain's natural focus-rest cycles), and Cal Newport's deep work approach (longer, phone-free sessions without rigid time boxing). Note which is best for which type of work.]</p>
